     185                 :           0 :     function sqrt(uint256 x) internal pure returns (uint256 z) {
     186                 :             :         /// @solidity memory-safe-assembly
     187                 :             :         assembly {
     188                 :           0 :             let y := x // We start y at x, which will help us make our initial estimate.
     189                 :             : 
     190                 :           0 :             z := 181 // The "correct" value is 1, but this saves a multiplication later.
     191                 :             : 
     192                 :             :             // This segment is to get a reasonable initial estimate for the Babylonian method. With a bad
     193                 :             :             // start, the correct # of bits increases ~linearly each iteration instead of ~quadratically.
     194                 :             : 
     195                 :             :             // We check y >= 2^(k + 8) but shift right by k bits
     196                 :             :             // each branch to ensure that if x >= 256, then y >= 256.
     197            [ # ]:           0 :             if iszero(lt(y, 0x10000000000000000000000000000000000)) {
     198                 :           0 :                 y := shr(128, y)
     199                 :           0 :                 z := shl(64, z)
     200                 :             :             }
     201            [ # ]:           0 :             if iszero(lt(y, 0x1000000000000000000)) {
     202                 :           0 :                 y := shr(64, y)
     203                 :           0 :                 z := shl(32, z)
     204                 :             :             }
     205            [ # ]:           0 :             if iszero(lt(y, 0x10000000000)) {
     206                 :           0 :                 y := shr(32, y)
     207                 :           0 :                 z := shl(16, z)
     208                 :             :             }
     209            [ # ]:           0 :             if iszero(lt(y, 0x1000000)) {
     210                 :           0 :                 y := shr(16, y)
     211                 :           0 :                 z := shl(8, z)
     212                 :             :             }
     213                 :             : 
     214                 :             :             // Goal was to get z*z*y within a small factor of x. More iterations could
     215                 :             :             // get y in a tighter range. Currently, we will have y in [256, 256*2^16).
     216                 :             :             // We ensured y >= 256 so that the relative difference between y and y+1 is small.
     217                 :             :             // That's not possible if x < 256 but we can just verify those cases exhaustively.
     218                 :             : 
     219                 :             :             // Now, z*z*y <= x < z*z*(y+1), and y <= 2^(16+8), and either y >= 256, or x < 256.
     220                 :             :             // Correctness can be checked exhaustively for x < 256, so we assume y >= 256.
     221                 :             :             // Then z*sqrt(y) is within sqrt(257)/sqrt(256) of sqrt(x), or about 20bps.
     222                 :             : 
     223                 :             :             // For s in the range [1/256, 256], the estimate f(s) = (181/1024) * (s+1) is in the range
     224                 :             :             // (1/2.84 * sqrt(s), 2.84 * sqrt(s)), with largest error when s = 1 and when s = 256 or 1/256.
     225                 :             : 
     226                 :             :             // Since y is in [256, 256*2^16), let a = y/65536, so that a is in [1/256, 256). Then we can estimate
     227                 :             :             // sqrt(y) using sqrt(65536) * 181/1024 * (a + 1) = 181/4 * (y + 65536)/65536 = 181 * (y + 65536)/2^18.
     228                 :             : 
     229                 :             :             // There is no overflow risk here since y < 2^136 after the first branch above.
     230                 :           0 :             z := shr(18, mul(z, add(y, 65536))) // A mul() is saved from starting z at 181.
     231                 :             : 
     232                 :             :             // Given the worst case multiplicative error of 2.84 above, 7 iterations should be enough.
     233                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     234                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     235                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     236                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     237                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     238                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     239                 :           0 :             z := shr(1, add(z, div(x, z)))
     240                 :             : 
     241                 :             :             // If x+1 is a perfect square, the Babylonian method cycles between
     242                 :             :             // floor(sqrt(x)) and ceil(sqrt(x)). This statement ensures we return floor.
     243                 :             :             // See: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_square_root#Using_only_integer_division
     244                 :             :             // Since the ceil is rare, we save gas on the assignment and repeat division in the rare case.
     245                 :             :             // If you don't care whether the floor or ceil square root is returned, you can remove this statement.
     246                 :           0 :             z := sub(z, lt(div(x, z), z))
     247                 :             :         }
     248                 :             :     }

     433                 :             : /**
     434                 :             :  * @title IOracleModule
     435                 :             :  * @dev Adapted from Euler's `IPriceOracle` interface
     436                 :             :  * <https://github.com/euler-xyz/euler-price-oracle/blob/ffc3cb82615fc7d003a7f431175bd1eaf0bf41c5/src/interfaces/IPriceOracle.sol>
     437                 :             :  *      - DYTM aims to use oracles as used by Euler.
     438                 :             :  *      - For getting prices in USD, as required by the Euler oracles (ERC7726), ISO 4217 code is used.
     439                 :             :  *        For USD, it is 840 so we use `address(840)` as the address for USD.
     440                 :             :  */
     441                 :             : interface IOracleModule {
     442                 :             :     /**
     443                 :             :      * @notice One-sided price: How much quote token you would get for inAmount of base token, assuming no price spread.
     444                 :             :      * @dev If `quote` is USD, the `outAmount` is in WAD.
     445                 :             :      * @param inAmount The amount of `base` to convert.
     446                 :             :      * @param base The token that is being priced.

     455                 :             : // OpenZeppelin Contracts (last updated v5.1.0) (utils/Panic.sol)
     456                 :             : 
     457                 :             : /**
     458                 :             :  * @dev Helper library for emitting standardized panic codes.
     459                 :             :  *
     460                 :             :  * ```solidity
     461                 :             :  * contract Example {
     462                 :             :  *      using Panic for uint256;
     463                 :             :  *
     464                 :             :  *      // Use any of the declared internal constants
     465                 :             :  *      function foo() { Panic.GENERIC.panic(); }
     466                 :             :  *
     467                 :             :  *      // Alternatively
     468                 :             :  *      function foo() { Panic.panic(Panic.GENERIC); }
     469                 :             :  * }
     470                 :             :  * ```
     471                 :             :  *
     472                 :             :  * Follows the list from https://github.com/ethereum/solidity/blob/v0.8.24/libsolutil/ErrorCodes.h[libsolutil].
     473                 :             :  *
     474                 :             :  * _Available since v5.1._
     475                 :             :  */
     476                 :             : // slither-disable-next-line unused-state
     477                 :             : library Panic {
     478                 :             :     /// @dev generic / unspecified error
     479                 :             :     uint256 internal constant GENERIC = 0x00;
     480                 :             :     /// @dev used by the assert() builtin
     481                 :             :     uint256 internal constant ASSERT = 0x01;
     482                 :             :     /// @dev arithmetic underflow or overflow
     483                 :             :     uint256 internal constant UNDER_OVERFLOW = 0x11;
     484                 :             :     /// @dev division or modulo by zero
     485                 :             :     uint256 internal constant DIVISION_BY_ZERO = 0x12;
     486                 :             :     /// @dev enum conversion error
     487                 :             :     uint256 internal constant ENUM_CONVERSION_ERROR = 0x21;
     488                 :             :     /// @dev invalid encoding in storage
     489                 :             :     uint256 internal constant STORAGE_ENCODING_ERROR = 0x22;
     490                 :             :     /// @dev empty array pop
     491                 :             :     uint256 internal constant EMPTY_ARRAY_POP = 0x31;
     492                 :             :     /// @dev array out of bounds access
     493                 :             :     uint256 internal constant ARRAY_OUT_OF_BOUNDS = 0x32;
     494                 :             :     /// @dev resource error (too large allocation or too large array)
     495                 :             :     uint256 internal constant RESOURCE_ERROR = 0x41;
     496                 :             :     /// @dev calling invalid internal function
     497                 :             :     uint256 internal constant INVALID_INTERNAL_FUNCTION = 0x51;
     498                 :             : 
     499                 :             :     /// @dev Reverts with a panic code. Recommended to use with
     500                 :             :     /// the internal constants with predefined codes.
     501                 :           0 :     function panic(uint256 code) internal pure {
     502                 :             :         assembly ("memory-safe") {
     503                 :           0 :             mstore(0x00, 0x4e487b71)
     504                 :           0 :             mstore(0x20, code)
     505                 :           0 :             revert(0x1c, 0x24)
     506                 :             :         }
     507                 :             :     }
     508                 :             : }

     514                 :             : 
     515                 :             : /**
     516                 :             :  * @dev Wrappers over Solidity's uintXX/intXX/bool casting operators with added overflow
     517                 :             :  * checks.
     518                 :             :  *
     519                 :             :  * Downcasting from uint256/int256 in Solidity does not revert on overflow. This can
     520                 :             :  * easily result in undesired exploitation or bugs, since developers usually
     521                 :             :  * assume that overflows raise errors. `SafeCast` restores this intuition by
     522                 :             :  * reverting the transaction when such an operation overflows.
     523                 :             :  *
     524                 :             :  * Using this library instead of the unchecked operations eliminates an entire
     525                 :             :  * class of bugs, so it's recommended to use it always.
     526                 :             :  */

    2022                 :             : 
    2023                 :             : /// @title SharesMathLib
    2024                 :             : /// @notice Shares management library.
    2025                 :             : /// @dev Mostly adapted from Morpho's SharesMathLib:
    2026                 :             : /// https://github.com/morpho-org/morpho-blue/blob/d89ca53ff6cbbacf8717a8ce819ee58f49bcc592/src/libraries/SharesMathLib.sol
    2027                 :             : /// @dev This implementation mitigates share price manipulations, using OpenZeppelin's method of virtual shares:
    2028                 :             : /// https://docs.openzeppelin.com/contracts/4.x/erc4626#inflation-attack.
    2029                 :             : /// @author Morpho Labs
    2030                 :             : /// @author Chinmay <chinmay@dhedge.org>
    2031                 :             : library SharesMathLib {
    2032                 :             :     using FixedPointMathLib for uint256;
    2033                 :             : 
    2034                 :             :     /// @dev The number of virtual shares has been chosen low enough to prevent overflows, and high enough to ensure
    2035                 :             :     ///      high precision computations.
    2036                 :             :     ///      - Virtual shares can never be redeemed for the assets they are entitled to, but it is assumed the share price
    2037                 :             :     ///        stays low enough not to inflate these assets to a significant value.
    2038                 :             :     ///      Warning: The assets to which virtual borrow shares are entitled behave like unrealizable bad debt.
    2039                 :             :     uint256 internal constant VIRTUAL_SHARES = 1e6;
    2040                 :             : 
    2041                 :             :     /// @dev A number of virtual assets of 1 enforces a conversion rate between shares and assets when a market is
    2042                 :             :     ///      empty.
    2043                 :             :     uint256 internal constant VIRTUAL_ASSETS = 1;
    2044                 :             : 
    2045                 :             :     /// @dev Calculates the value of `assets` quoted in shares, rounding down.
    2046                 :           0 :     function toSharesDown(
    2047                 :             :         uint256 assets,
    2048                 :             :         uint256 totalAssets,
    2049                 :             :         uint256 totalShares
    2050                 :             :     )
    2051                 :             :         internal
    2052                 :             :         pure
    2053                 :             :         returns (uint256 shares)
    2054                 :             :     {
    2055                 :           0 :         return assets.mulDivDown(totalShares + VIRTUAL_SHARES, totalAssets + VIRTUAL_ASSETS);
    2056                 :             :     }
    2057                 :             : 
    2058                 :             :     /// @dev Calculates the value of `shares` quoted in assets, rounding down.
    2059                 :           0 :     function toAssetsDown(
    2060                 :             :         uint256 shares,
    2061                 :             :         uint256 totalAssets,
    2062                 :             :         uint256 totalShares
    2063                 :             :     )
    2064                 :             :         internal
    2065                 :             :         pure
    2066                 :             :         returns (uint256 assets)
    2067                 :             :     {
    2068                 :           0 :         return shares.mulDivDown(totalAssets + VIRTUAL_ASSETS, totalShares + VIRTUAL_SHARES);
    2069                 :             :     }
    2070                 :             : 
    2071                 :             :     /// @dev Calculates the value of `assets` quoted in shares, rounding up.
    2072                 :           0 :     function toSharesUp(
    2073                 :             :         uint256 assets,
    2074                 :             :         uint256 totalAssets,
    2075                 :             :         uint256 totalShares
    2076                 :             :     )
    2077                 :             :         internal
    2078                 :             :         pure
    2079                 :             :         returns (uint256 shares)
    2080                 :             :     {
    2081                 :           0 :         return assets.mulDivUp(totalShares + VIRTUAL_SHARES, totalAssets + VIRTUAL_ASSETS);
    2082                 :             :     }
    2083                 :             : 
    2084                 :             :     /// @dev Calculates the value of `shares` quoted in assets, rounding up.
    2085                 :           0 :     function toAssetsUp(
    2086                 :             :         uint256 shares,
    2087                 :             :         uint256 totalAssets,
    2088                 :             :         uint256 totalShares
    2089                 :             :     )
    2090                 :             :         internal
    2091                 :             :         pure
    2092                 :             :         returns (uint256 assets)

    2239                 :             :      * The result is stored in two 256 variables such that sum = high * 2 + low.
    2240                 :             :      */

    2242                 :             :         assembly ("memory-safe") {
    2243                 :           0 :             low := add(a, b)
    2244                 :           0 :             high := lt(low, a)

    2249                 :             :      * @dev Return the 512-bit multiplication of two uint256.
    2250                 :             :      *
    2251                 :             :      * The result is stored in two 256 variables such that product = high * 2 + low.
    2252                 :             :      */
    2253                 :           0 :     function mul512(uint256 a, uint256 b) internal pure returns (uint256 high, uint256 low) {
    2254                 :             :         // 512-bit multiply [high low] = x * y. Compute the product mod 2 and mod 2 - 1, then use
    2255                 :             :         // the Chinese Remainder Theorem to reconstruct the 512 bit result. The result is stored in two 256
    2256                 :             :         // variables such that product = high * 2 + low.
    2257                 :             :         assembly ("memory-safe") {
    2258                 :           0 :             let mm := mulmod(a, b, not(0))
    2259                 :           0 :             low := mul(a, b)
    2260                 :           0 :             high := sub(sub(mm, low), lt(mm, low))
    2261                 :             :         }
    2262                 :             :     }

    2351                 :             : 
    2352                 :             :     /**
    2353                 :             :      * @dev Branchless ternary evaluation for `a ? b : c`. Gas costs are constant.
    2354                 :             :      *
    2355                 :             :      * IMPORTANT: This function may reduce bytecode size and consume less gas when used standalone.
    2356                 :             :      * However, the compiler may optimize Solidity ternary operations (i.e. `a ? b : c`) to only compute
    2357                 :             :      * one branch when needed, making this function more expensive.
    2358                 :             :      */

    2400                 :           0 :             Panic.panic(Panic.DIVISION_BY_ZERO);

    2420                 :           0 :     function mulDiv(uint256 x, uint256 y, uint256 denominator) internal pure returns (uint256 result) {
    2421                 :             :         unchecked {
    2422                 :           0 :             (uint256 high, uint256 low) = mul512(x, y);
    2423                 :             : 
    2424                 :             :             // Handle non-overflow cases, 256 by 256 division.

    2426                 :             :                 // Solidity will revert if denominator == 0, unlike the div opcode on its own.
    2427                 :             :                 // The surrounding unchecked block does not change this fact.

    2432                 :             :             // Make sure the result is less than 2. Also prevents denominator == 0.
    2433            [ # ]:           0 :             if (denominator <= high) {
    2434                 :           0 :                 Panic.panic(ternary(denominator == 0, Panic.DIVISION_BY_ZERO, Panic.UNDER_OVERFLOW));
    2435                 :             :             }
    2436                 :             : 
    2437                 :             :             ///////////////////////////////////////////////
    2438                 :             :             // 512 by 256 division.
    2439                 :             :             ///////////////////////////////////////////////
    2440                 :             : 
    2441                 :             :             // Make division exact by subtracting the remainder from [high low].
    2442                 :           0 :             uint256 remainder;
    2443                 :             :             assembly ("memory-safe") {
    2444                 :             :                 // Compute remainder using mulmod.
    2445                 :           0 :                 remainder := mulmod(x, y, denominator)
    2446                 :             : 
    2447                 :             :                 // Subtract 256 bit number from 512 bit number.
    2448                 :           0 :                 high := sub(high, gt(remainder, low))
    2449                 :           0 :                 low := sub(low, remainder)
    2450                 :             :             }

    2453                 :             :             // Always >= 1. See https://cs.stackexchange.com/q/138556/92363.
    2454                 :             :

    2457                 :             :                 // Divide denominator by twos.
    2458                 :           0 :                 denominator := div(denominator, twos)

    2460                 :             :                 // Divide [high low] by twos.

    2464                 :           0 :                 twos := add(div(sub(0, twos), twos), 1)

    2471                 :             :             // that denominator * inv  1 mod 2. Compute the inverse by starting with a seed that is correct for
    2472                 :             :             // four bits. That is, denominator * inv  1 mod 2.

    2476                 :             :             // works in modular arithmetic, doubling the correct bits in each step.
    2477                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2
    2478                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2
    2479                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2
    2480                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2
    2481                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2
    2482                 :           0 :             inverse *= 2 - denominator * inverse; // inverse mod 2

    2520                 :             :     /**
    2521                 :             :      * @dev Calculate the modular multiplicative inverse of a number in Z/nZ.
    2522                 :             :      *
    2523                 :             :      * If n is a prime, then Z/nZ is a field. In that case all elements are inversible, except 0.
    2524                 :             :      * If n is not a prime, then Z/nZ is not a field, and some elements might not be inversible.
    2525                 :             :      *
    2526                 :             :      * If the input value is not inversible, 0 is returned.
    2527                 :             :      *
    2528                 :             :      * NOTE: If you know for sure that n is (big) a prime, it may be cheaper to use Fermat's little theorem and get the
    2529                 :             :      * inverse using `Math.modExp(a, n - 2, n)`. See {invModPrime}.
    2530                 :             :      */
    2531                 :           0 :     function invMod(uint256 a, uint256 n) internal pure returns (uint256) {
    2532                 :             :         unchecked {
    2533            [ # ]:           0 :             if (n == 0) return 0;
    2534                 :             : 
    2535                 :             :             // The inverse modulo is calculated using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm (iterative version)
    2536                 :             :             // Used to compute integers x and y such that: ax + ny = gcd(a, n).
    2537                 :             :             // When the gcd is 1, then the inverse of a modulo n exists and it's x.
    2538                 :             :             // ax + ny = 1
    2539                 :             :             // ax = 1 + (-y)n
    2540                 :             :             // ax  1 (mod n) # x is the inverse of a modulo n
    2541                 :             : 
    2542                 :             :             // If the remainder is 0 the gcd is n right away.
    2543                 :           0 :             uint256 remainder = a % n;
    2544                 :           0 :             uint256 gcd = n;
    2545                 :             : 
    2546                 :             :             // Therefore the initial coefficients are:
    2547                 :             :             // ax + ny = gcd(a, n) = n
    2548                 :             :             // 0a + 1n = n
    2549                 :           0 :             int256 x = 0;
    2550                 :           0 :             int256 y = 1;
    2551                 :             : 
    2552                 :           0 :             while (remainder != 0) {
    2553                 :           0 :                 uint256 quotient = gcd / remainder;
    2554                 :             : 
    2555                 :           0 :                 (gcd, remainder) = (
    2556                 :             :                     // The old remainder is the next gcd to try.
    2557                 :             :                     remainder,
    2558                 :             :                     // Compute the next remainder.
    2559                 :             :                     // Can't overflow given that (a % gcd) * (gcd // (a % gcd)) <= gcd
    2560                 :             :                     // where gcd is at most n (capped to type(uint256).max)
    2561                 :             :                     gcd - remainder * quotient
    2562                 :             :                 );
    2563                 :             : 
    2564                 :           0 :                 (x, y) = (
    2565                 :             :                     // Increment the coefficient of a.
    2566                 :             :                     y,
    2567                 :             :                     // Decrement the coefficient of n.
    2568                 :             :                     // Can overflow, but the result is casted to uint256 so that the
    2569                 :             :                     // next value of y is "wrapped around" to a value between 0 and n - 1.
    2570                 :             :                     x - y * int256(quotient)
    2571                 :             :                 );
    2572                 :             :             }
    2573                 :             : 
    2574            [ # ]:           0 :             if (gcd != 1) return 0; // No inverse exists.
    2575                 :           0 :             return ternary(x < 0, n - uint256(-x), uint256(x)); // Wrap the result if it's negative.
    2576                 :             :         }
    2577                 :             :     }

    2701                 :             :     /**
    2702                 :             :      * @dev Returns the square root of a number. If the number is not a perfect square, the value is rounded
    2703                 :             :      * towards zero.
    2704                 :             :      *
    2705                 :             :      * This method is based on Newton's method for computing square roots; the algorithm is restricted to only
    2706                 :             :      * using integer operations.
    2707                 :             :      */
    2708                 :           0 :     function sqrt(uint256 a) internal pure returns (uint256) {
    2709                 :             :         unchecked {
    2710                 :             :             // Take care of easy edge cases when a == 0 or a == 1
    2711            [ # ]:           0 :             if (a <= 1) {
    2712                 :           0 :                 return a;
    2713                 :             :             }
    2714                 :             : 
    2715                 :             :             // In this function, we use Newton's method to get a root of `f(x) := x - a`. It involves building a
    2716                 :             :             // sequence x_n that converges toward sqrt(a). For each iteration x_n, we also define the error between
    2717                 :             :             // the current value as `_n = | x_n - sqrt(a) |`.
    2718                 :             :             //
    2719                 :             :             // For our first estimation, we consider `e` the smallest power of 2 which is bigger than the square root
    2720                 :             :             // of the target. (i.e. `2**(e-1)  sqrt(a) < 2**e`). We know that `e  128` because `(2) = 2` is
    2721                 :             :             // bigger than any uint256.
    2722                 :             :             //
    2723                 :             :             // By noticing that
    2724                 :             :             // `2**(e-1)  sqrt(a) < 2**e  (2**(e-1))  a < (2**e)  2**(2*e-2)  a < 2**(2*e)`
    2725                 :             :             // we can deduce that `e - 1` is `log2(a) / 2`. We can thus compute `x_n = 2**(e-1)` using a method similar
    2726                 :             :             // to the msb function.
    2727                 :           0 :             uint256 aa = a;
    2728                 :           0 :             uint256 xn = 1;
    2729                 :             : 
    2730            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 128)) {
    2731                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 128;
    2732                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 64;
    2733                 :             :             }
    2734            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 64)) {
    2735                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 64;
    2736                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 32;
    2737                 :             :             }
    2738            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 32)) {
    2739                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 32;
    2740                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 16;
    2741                 :             :             }
    2742            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 16)) {
    2743                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 16;
    2744                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 8;
    2745                 :             :             }
    2746            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 8)) {
    2747                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 8;
    2748                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 4;
    2749                 :             :             }
    2750            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 4)) {
    2751                 :           0 :                 aa >>= 4;
    2752                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 2;
    2753                 :             :             }
    2754            [ # ]:           0 :             if (aa >= (1 << 2)) {
    2755                 :           0 :                 xn <<= 1;
    2756                 :             :             }
    2757                 :             : 
    2758                 :             :             // We now have x_n such that `x_n = 2**(e-1)  sqrt(a) < 2**e = 2 * x_n`. This implies _n  2**(e-1).
    2759                 :             :             //
    2760                 :             :             // We can refine our estimation by noticing that the middle of that interval minimizes the error.
    2761                 :             :             // If we move x_n to equal 2**(e-1) + 2**(e-2), then we reduce the error to _n  2**(e-2).
    2762                 :             :             // This is going to be our x_0 (and _0)
    2763                 :           0 :             xn = (3 * xn) >> 1; // _0 := | x_0 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-2)
    2764                 :             : 
    2765                 :             :             // From here, Newton's method give us:
    2766                 :             :             // x_{n+1} = (x_n + a / x_n) / 2
    2767                 :             :             //
    2768                 :             :             // One should note that:
    2769                 :             :             // x_{n+1} - a = ((x_n + a / x_n) / 2) - a
    2770                 :             :             //              = ((x_n + a) / (2 * x_n)) - a
    2771                 :             :             //              = (x_n + 2 * a * x_n + a) / (4 * x_n) - a
    2772                 :             :             //              = (x_n + 2 * a * x_n + a - 4 * a * x_n) / (4 * x_n)
    2773                 :             :             //              = (x_n - 2 * a * x_n + a) / (4 * x_n)
    2774                 :             :             //              = (x_n - a) / (2 * x_n)
    2775                 :             :             //              = ((x_n - a) / (2 * x_n))
    2776                 :             :             //               0
    2777                 :             :             // Which proves that for all n  1, sqrt(a)  x_n
    2778                 :             :             //
    2779                 :             :             // This gives us the proof of quadratic convergence of the sequence:
    2780                 :             :             // _{n+1} = | x_{n+1} - sqrt(a) |
    2781                 :             :             //         = | (x_n + a / x_n) / 2 - sqrt(a) |
    2782                 :             :             //         = | (x_n + a - 2*x_n*sqrt(a)) / (2 * x_n) |
    2783                 :             :             //         = | (x_n - sqrt(a)) / (2 * x_n) |
    2784                 :             :             //         = | _n / (2 * x_n) |
    2785                 :             :             //         = _n / | (2 * x_n) |
    2786                 :             :             //
    2787                 :             :             // For the first iteration, we have a special case where x_0 is known:
    2788                 :             :             // _1 = _0 / | (2 * x_0) |
    2789                 :             :             //      (2**(e-2)) / (2 * (2**(e-1) + 2**(e-2)))
    2790                 :             :             //      2**(2*e-4) / (3 * 2**(e-1))
    2791                 :             :             //      2**(e-3) / 3
    2792                 :             :             //      2**(e-3-log2(3))
    2793                 :             :             //      2**(e-4.5)
    2794                 :             :             //
    2795                 :             :             // For the following iterations, we use the fact that, 2**(e-1)  sqrt(a)  x_n:
    2796                 :             :             // _{n+1} = _n / | (2 * x_n) |
    2797                 :             :             //          (2**(e-k)) / (2 * 2**(e-1))
    2798                 :             :             //          2**(2*e-2*k) / 2**e
    2799                 :             :             //          2**(e-2*k)
    2800                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _1 := | x_1 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-4.5)  -- special case, see above
    2801                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _2 := | x_2 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-9)    -- general case with k = 4.5
    2802                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _3 := | x_3 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-18)   -- general case with k = 9
    2803                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _4 := | x_4 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-36)   -- general case with k = 18
    2804                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _5 := | x_5 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-72)   -- general case with k = 36
    2805                 :           0 :             xn = (xn + a / xn) >> 1; // _6 := | x_6 - sqrt(a) |  2**(e-144)  -- general case with k = 72
    2806                 :             : 
    2807                 :             :             // Because e  128 (as discussed during the first estimation phase), we know have reached a precision

    2809                 :             :             // sqrt(a) or sqrt(a) + 1.

    2811                 :             :         }

    3908                 :             : 
    3909                 :             : /**
    3910                 :             :  * @dev Library for managing
    3911                 :             :  * https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(abstract_data_type)[sets] of primitive
    3912                 :             :  * types.
    3913                 :             :  *
    3914                 :             :  * Sets have the following properties:
    3915                 :             :  *
    3916                 :             :  * - Elements are added, removed, and checked for existence in constant time
    3917                 :             :  * (O(1)).
    3918                 :             :  * - Elements are enumerated in O(n). No guarantees are made on the ordering.
    3919                 :             :  * - Set can be cleared (all elements removed) in O(n).
    3920                 :             :  *
    3921                 :             :  * ```solidity
    3922                 :             :  * contract Example {
    3923                 :             :  *     // Add the library methods
    3924                 :             :  *     using EnumerableSet for EnumerableSet.AddressSet;
    3925                 :             :  *
    3926                 :             :  *     // Declare a set state variable
    3927                 :             :  *     EnumerableSet.AddressSet private mySet;
    3928                 :             :  * }
    3929                 :             :  * ```
    3930                 :             :  *
    3931                 :             :  * As of v3.3.0, sets of type `bytes32` (`Bytes32Set`), `address` (`AddressSet`)
    3932                 :             :  * and `uint256` (`UintSet`) are supported.
    3933                 :             :  *
    3934                 :             :  * [WARNING]
    3935                 :             :  * ====
    3936                 :             :  * Trying to delete such a structure from storage will likely result in data corruption, rendering the structure
    3937                 :             :  * unusable.
    3938                 :             :  * See https://github.com/ethereum/solidity/pull/11843[ethereum/solidity#11843] for more info.
    3939                 :             :  *
    3940                 :             :  * In order to clean an EnumerableSet, you can either remove all elements one by one or create a fresh instance using an
    3941                 :             :  * array of EnumerableSet.
    3942                 :             :  * ====
    3943                 :             :  */
    3944                 :             : library EnumerableSet {
    3945                 :             :     // To implement this library for multiple types with as little code
    3946                 :             :     // repetition as possible, we write it in terms of a generic Set type with
    3947                 :             :     // bytes32 values.
    3948                 :             :     // The Set implementation uses private functions, and user-facing
    3949                 :             :     // implementations (such as AddressSet) are just wrappers around the
    3950                 :             :     // underlying Set.
    3951                 :             :     // This means that we can only create new EnumerableSets for types that fit
    3952                 :             :     // in bytes32.
    3953                 :             : 
    3954                 :             :     struct Set {
    3955                 :             :         // Storage of set values
    3956                 :             :         bytes32[] _values;

    4684                 :             :     /// @dev We encode the account Id and the market Id into a single uint256 and store it in the table.
    4685                 :             :     ///      This is possible because the market Id is at most 88 bits and the account Id is at most 160 bits
    4686                 :             :     ///      even though the underlying account Id type is 256 bits, only the upper 96 bits are useful for isolated accounts
    4687                 :             :     ///      and only the lower 160 bits are useful for user accounts. In short, this is a bijective function.

    4692                 :           0 :         uint256 rawAccount = AccountId.unwrap(account);
    4693                 :           0 :         uint88 rawMarket = MarketId.unwrap(market);
    4694                 :             : 
    4695                 :           0 :         bool isIsolatedAccount = account.isIsolatedAccount();
    4696                 :             : 
    4697         [ #  # ]:           0 :         if (isIsolatedAccount) {
    4698                 :             :             // Although the actual isolated account ID is in the upper 96 bits,
    4699                 :             :             // we only need to shift right by 159 as the LSB is always 0 for isolated accounts.
    4700                 :             :             // The lower 160 bits of an isolated account ID are always 0.
    4701                 :           0 :             uint256 rawIsolatedAccount = uint256(rawAccount >> 159);
    4702                 :             : 
    4703                 :             :             // Isolated account: upper 88 bits = market, next 96 bits = account, LSB = 1
    4704                 :           0 :             encoded = (uint256(rawMarket) << 168) | rawIsolatedAccount | 1;
    4705                 :             :         } else {

    4707                 :             :             // we do it this way to set the LSB to 0.
    4708                 :           0 :             uint256 rawUserAccount = rawAccount << 1;
    4709                 :             : 
    4710                 :             :             // User account: upper 88 bits = market, next 160 bits = account, LSB = 0
    4711                 :           0 :             encoded = (uint256(rawMarket) << 168) | rawUserAccount;
    4712                 :             :         }
    4713                 :             :     }

    5234                 :             :      * - The liquidator must approve enough debt asset amount to the Office for repayment.
    5235                 :             :      *

    5237                 :             :      * > - Regardless of bad debt accrual, the liquidator will always receive a bonus.
    5238                 :             :      * > - To change this behaviour, the officer can change the bonus percentage to 0 using the before liquidation hook.
    5239                 :             :      *     However, this will make the job of liquidators harder as they need to calculate the exact amount of

    5259                 :             : 
    5260                 :             :     /**
    5261                 :             :      * @notice Function to split an account into two accounts.
    5262                 :             :      *
    5263                 :             :      * - Creates a new isolated account that gets a portion of the debt asset and collateral assets.
    5264                 :             :      * - The original account retains the remaining portion of the assets.
    5265                 :             :      * - Particularly useful for vaults which don't want to maintain instant withdrawal liquidity and to ease withdrawals.
    5266                 :             :      * - Only the original account's health is checked before splitting given that the portion receiver will always be a new account
    5267                 :             :      *   and a proportional split will not affect the original account's health.
    5268                 :             :      *
    5269                 :             :      * > [!WARNING]
    5270                 :             :      * > If the market values health of accounts differently (for example using hooks),

    5765                 :             : /// @title Registry
    5766                 :             : /// @notice Tokenization as inspired by ERC6909.
    5767                 :             : /// @dev May not be fully compliant with the ERC6909 standard because of the following reasons:
    5768                 :             : ///      - The `transferFrom` function does not allow transferring isolated account tokens by operators
    5769                 :             : ///        unless the caller explicitly approved them.
    5770                 :             : ///      - The operator scope is not limited to transfers but allows full market functions' access except for transferring
    5771                 :             : ///        the account itself.
    5772                 :             : ///      - The `approve` function does not allow approving debt tokens.
    5773                 :             : /// @author Chinmay <chinmay@dhedge.org>

    5775                 :             :     using AccountIdLibrary for *;

    6131                 :             :     /// @dev Sets `amount` as the allowance of `spender` over the `from`'s `tokenId` tokens.
    6132                 :             :     ///

    6136                 :             :     /// Emits an {Approval} event.

    6138                 :             :     /// Requirements:
    6139                 :             :     /// - `from` cannot be the zero AccountId.
    6140                 :             :     /// - `spender` cannot be the zero AccountId.

    6968                 :             :     /// @dev This function WILL NOT revert even if the asset is not borrowable.
    6969                 :           0 :     function _accrueInterest(ReserveKey key, IMarketConfig marketConfig) internal returns (uint256 interest) {
    6970                 :           0 :         ReserveData storage $reserveData = getReserveDataStorage(key);
    6971                 :           0 :         uint64 feePercentage = marketConfig.feePercentage();
    6972                 :           0 :         uint256 dt = block.timestamp - $reserveData.lastUpdateTimestamp;
    6973                 :             : 
    6974                 :             :         // In case no time has passed since the last update or the reserve is not borrowable we simply return 0.
    6975            [ # ]:           0 :         if (dt == 0 || !marketConfig.isBorrowableAsset(key.getAsset())) {
    6976                 :           0 :             return 0;
    6977                 :             :         }
    6978                 :             : 
    6979                 :             :         // Computing the compounded interest accrued over the time interval `dt`.
    6980                 :             :         // We use first 3 terms of the Taylor series expansion for e^(rt) - 1 as an approximation.
    6981                 :             :         {
    6982                 :           0 :             uint256 ratePerSecond = marketConfig.irm().borrowRate(key);
    6983                 :           0 :             uint256 rt = ratePerSecond * dt;
    6984                 :           0 :             uint256 rt2 = rt.mulDivDown(rt, 2 * WAD);
    6985                 :           0 :             uint256 rt3 = rt2.mulDivDown(rt, 3 * WAD);
    6986                 :             : 
    6987                 :           0 :             interest = $reserveData.borrowed.mulWadDown(rt + rt2 + rt3);
    6988                 :             : 
    6989                 :             :             // Update both the reserve data.
    6990                 :           0 :             $reserveData.supplied += interest;
    6991                 :           0 :             $reserveData.borrowed += interest;
    6992                 :           0 :             $reserveData.lastUpdateTimestamp = uint128(block.timestamp);
